[1] Case updates
- Wed 25 Dec 2019. CMRE (Comite Multisectoriel de la Riposte a la maladie a virus Ebola)
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://crofsblogs.typepad.com/h5n1/2019/12/drc-ebola-cmre-update-december-25.html

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 24 Dec 2019:

Since the start of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases has been 3366, of which 3248 are confirmed and 118 probable. In total, there were 2227 deaths (2109 confirmed and 118 probable) and 1098 people recovered.
- 392 suspected cases under investigation;
- 3 new confirmed cases in North Kivu, including 2 in Kalunguta and 1 in Mabalako;
- Kalunguta re-notified confirmed cases after 63 days of silence;
- No new deaths among the confirmed cases, including no community death among the confirmed cases and no death among the confirmed cases;
- No healed person has left the CTE;
- No health worker is among the new confirmed cases. The cumulative number of confirmed / probable cases among health workers is 164 (approximately 5% of all confirmed / probable cases), including 41 deaths.

Interception of 2 high-risk contacts at the Maboya checkpoint
- 2 high-risk contacts were intercepted at the Maboya checkpoint;
- These are 2 men aged 47 and 14, from Cantine / Aloya bound for Butembo. They are the biker's contacts, confirmed case of 16 Dec 2019 in Aloya. The 2 subjects were sent to the Ebola treatment center (ETC) in Butembo;
- In addition, at the Foner checkpoint in Mambasa in Ituri, there was theft of response materials during the night of 23-24 Dec 2019;
- It is a handwashing device, including a tank with a capacity of 2000 l [528 gal] carried by individuals not otherwise identified;
- Assaults on 2 service providers at the Goma Public Port control point were also reported by the agents of the security firm GSA, because they demanded that they strictly observe the hygiene measures laid down at a control point.

Kalunguta health zone reports 2 Ebola cases after 63 days of silence

- The 1st case concerns a 7-year-old girl, alive, vaccinated in 2018 and not listed as a contact;
- The beginning of the signs dates back to 18 Dec 2019 with the date of the exposure period from 1-14 Dec 2019 by fever, anorexia, physical asthenia, chills, abdominal pain, and vomiting;
- From 18-24 Dec 2019, this child was hospitalized at the Kasinga / Mbunduku health post. Her evolution was marked by the occurrence of gingivorrhagia and melaena on 23 Dec 2019;
- This patient was transferred on 24 Dec 2019 by mototaxi to the Avo health post in the Kanyihunga health area. She was accompanied by her father and aunt. The alert was launched by the active research team, and the child was transferred by ambulance to the Ebola treatment center in Butembo after validation as a suspect case. It was confirmed the same day;
- The 2nd confirmed case is a 5-year-old girl, alive, unvaccinated and not listed as a contact. She is the sister of the 1st case;
- On 19 Dec 2019, this child was kept at home and without treatment. She was hospitalized and looked after by her mother at the Mbukudu dispensary from 20-24 Dec 2019 to be transferred on 24 Dec 2019 to the Avo health post in the Kanyihunga health area following the worsening of the signs and the occurrence of diarrhea, arthralgia, and melaena. She was accompanied by her father and aunt on mototaxi;
- She was transferred, after validation as a suspect case, by ambulance to the CTE of Butembo at the same time as her sister (the 7-year-old girl). She was confirmed Ebola the same day;
- Investigations around these 2 cases are continuing to establish their source of contamination. A total of 15 contacts have already been pre-listed around these cases.

Vaccination

- 2938 people were vaccinated, until 20 Dec 2019, with the 2nd vaccine Ad26.ZEBOV / MVA-BN-Filo (Johnson & Johnson) in the 2 health areas from Karisimbi to Goma;
- Since the start of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018 with the rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine, 259 276 people have been vaccinated.

Entry point surveillance

- Since the start of the epidemic, the total number of travelers checked (temperature taken) at health checkpoints has been 131 235 428;
- To date, a total of 109 entry points (PoE) and health control points (PoC) have been established in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri in order to protect the country's major cities and avoid the spread of the epidemic in neighboring countries.

--
